Data Cleaning & Transformation¶

This step transforms the json format data into panda dataframe with selected attributes. Some values in the column are transformed into appropriate data type or format (e.g., change price[str] into price[int]). I extracted [year,make,model] from the attribute title by splitting the string. Some NA values are removed and filled by mode.

In [54]:
rows=[]
for i in tqdm(car_data):
    row={}
    row['ID']=i
    for k,v in car_data[i]['vehicle_head_info'].items():
        row[k]=v
    for k,v in car_data[i]['seller_info'].items():
        row[k]=v
    for k,v in car_data[i]['basics'].items():
        row[k]=v
    row['features']=len(car_data[i]['all_features'])
    rows.append(row)

In [266]:
#define some functions for mapping 
#might be a bit tedious but I personally prefer writing functions 
def to_int(x):
    if isinstance(x, str):
        x=x.replace('$','')
        x=x.replace(',','')
        x=int(x)
    else:
        x=x
    return x

def to_flt(x):
    if isinstance(x, str):
        try:
            x=float(x)
        except:
            x=4.0
    else:
        x=float(x)
    return x
def review(x):
    if isinstance(x, str):
        x=int(x.replace(' Reviews',''))
    return x
        
def odor(x):
    if isinstance(x, str):
        x=x.replace('miles','').replace(',','')
        x=int(x)
    return x
def year(x):
    year=[int(s) for s in x.split() if s.isdigit()][0]
    return year
def brand(x):
    brand=[s for s in x.replace('Certified','').split() if not s.isdigit()][0]
    return brand
def model(x):
    model=x.replace('Certified','')
    try:
        model=model.split()[2]
    except: 
        model=model[5:]
    return model
def city(x):
    if isinstance(x,str):
        x=x.split(',')[0]
    else:
        x='unknown'
    return x
def state(x):
    if isinstance(x,str):
        x=x.split(',')[1][0:2]
    else:
        x='CA'
    return x
In [406]:
#replace missing value in seller_reviews_count with 0, missing ratings will be 4.0
car = pd.DataFrame(rows)
car.fillna(car.mode(),inplace = True)

car['seller_rating']=car['seller_rateing'].apply(to_flt).fillna(4.0)
car['seller_reviews_count']=car['seller_reviews_count'].apply(review)
car['Mileage']=car['odometer'].apply(odor)
car['year']=car['title'].apply(year)
car['make']=car['title'].apply(brand)
car['model']=car['title'].apply(model)
car['price']=car['price'].apply(to_int).dropna()
car['seller_city']=car['seller_position'].apply(city)
car['seller_state']=car['seller_position'].apply(state)
car['seller_reviews_count']=car['seller_reviews_count'].fillna(0)

car=car.drop(columns=['Trim', 'seller_rateing','seller_notes','odometer','seller_position'])
car=car.dropna(subset=['price','Mileage'])

Random Forest Tree¶

The result turns out to be quite great as the accuracy reaches over 95%.

In [510]:
X=car_features
y=car_features['price']
from sklearn.preprocessing import scale
# subset all categorical variables
cars_categorical = X.select_dtypes(include=['object'])
# convert into dummies
cars_dummies = pd.get_dummies(cars_categorical, drop_first=True)
# drop categorical variables 
X = X.drop(list(cars_categorical.columns), axis=1)
# concat dummy variables with X
X = pd.concat([X, cars_dummies], axis=1)
cols = X.columns
X = pd.DataFrame(scale(X))
X.columns = cols
y=y.reset_index()['price']
